     "firstPrinciples": "A remote Foundry project is just a set of service resources behind HTTPS. Python cannot touch those resources directly; it needs a library that knows the REST routes, shapes requests, authenticates each call, and turns responses into Python objects.",
     "definition": "The azure-ai-projects package is the Microsoft Foundry SDK package for Python. Its main entry point is azure.ai.projects.AIProjectClient, which gives code-first access to project resources such as agents, connections, deployments, datasets, indexes, evaluation rules, telemetry, and an authenticated OpenAI client.",
     "analogy": "Think of Foundry as a well-guarded workshop. The project endpoint is the workshop address, the credential is your badge, and AIProjectClient is the organized tool chest that knows which drawer holds each project tool.",
     "mentalModel": "Start with package then client then operation group. The package is installed once, the client is constructed per project endpoint, and operation groups are used for focused tasks.",
     "diagram": "flowchart LR\nPythonApp[Python app] --> Package[azure ai projects package]\nPackage --> Client[AIProjectClient]\nClient --> Project[Foundry project]\nProject --> Resources[Agents connections deployments datasets indexes]",
     "code": {
      "language": "python",
      "caption": "Print the project client type after constructing it from the endpoint.",
      "content": "import os\nfrom azure.identity import DefaultAzureCredential\nfrom azure.ai.projects import AIProjectClient\n\nendpoint = os.environ[\"FOUNDRY_PROJECT_ENDPOINT\"]\n\nwith DefaultAzureCredential() as credential, AIProjectClient(\n    endpoint=endpoint,\n    credential=credential,\n) as project_client:\n    print(type(project_client).__name__)\n"
     },
