     "id": "versions-lifecycle-migration",
     "title": "Version pinning, auto-update, and retirement",
     "term": "Model lifecycle",
     "tags": [
      "versions",
      "retirement",
      "migration"
     ],
     "firstPrinciples": "Models are living software. A deployment that works today can drift through updates or stop at retirement unless you choose version policy and migration strategy deliberately.",
     "definition": "Foundry lifecycle stages include Preview, Generally Available, Legacy, Deprecated, and Retired. Azure OpenAI deployment version policies include OnceNewDefaultVersionAvailable, OnceCurrentVersionExpired, and NoAutoUpgrade where supported. Pinning a specific model version improves repeatability, but retirement still requires migration. Retired models no longer serve inference and docs describe 410 Gone.",
     "analogy": "A model version is a textbook edition. Pinning means teaching from edition 3; retirement means edition 3 leaves the bookstore and you must migrate to edition 4.",
     "mentalModel": "For production, pin versions or use conservative upgrade policy, track retirement schedules, deploy replacement versions in parallel, test quality and latency, then cut over application configuration or alias use. For experiments, auto-update to default can be acceptable.",
     "diagram": "flowchart LR\n  Preview --> GA\n  GA --> Legacy\n  Legacy --> Deprecated\n  Deprecated --> Retired\n  Old[old deployment] --> New[test replacement]\n  New --> Cutover[planned cutover]",
     "code": {
      "language": "bash",
      "caption": "Read model version and version upgrade option.",
      "content": "az login --identity\n\naz cognitiveservices account deployment show   --resource-group \"<resource-group>\"   --name \"<foundry-or-openai-account-name>\"   --deployment-name \"<deployment-name>\"   --query \"{model:properties.model, versionUpgradeOption:properties.versionUpgradeOption, state:properties.provisioningState}\"\n\n# Microsoft Learn notes Azure CLI can read versionUpgradeOption; update support may require ARM or other supported tooling.\n"
     },
     "drills": [
      {
       "q": "Why pin a model version?",
       "a": "To preserve behavior while you validate future versions."
      },
      {
       "q": "What happens at retirement?",
       "a": "The model no longer serves; requests can return 410 Gone."
      },
      {
       "q": "What is the safest migration pattern?",
       "a": "Deploy a replacement in parallel, test it, then cut over intentionally."
      }
     ],
     "teachBack": "Version policy is production hygiene. I choose whether to pin or auto-update, then track retirement. Migration is a planned parallel deployment and cutover, not an emergency.",
     "glossary": [
      {
       "term": "Preview",
       "definition": "Experimental lifecycle stage."
      },
      {
       "term": "GA",
       "definition": "Generally Available production stage."
      },
      {
       "term": "Deprecated",
       "definition": "Restricted stage before retirement."
      },
      {
       "term": "Retired",
       "definition": "No longer serving inference."
      },
      {
       "term": "Version upgrade option",
       "definition": "Policy controlling supported automatic version updates."
      }
     ],
