     "firstPrinciples": "First principles: a client is a disciplined protocol peer. It starts the transport, performs initialize, discovers capabilities, then calls only what the server advertised.",
     "definition": "The Python SDK can build clients with ClientSession and transports such as stdio_client. A minimal client launches a local server process, initializes the MCP session, lists tools, and calls one tool with arguments.",
     "analogy": "The client is a radio operator following procedure: open channel, perform comms check, ask for the catalog, then send a numbered request.",
     "mentalModel": "Learn the client flow before relying on a host UI. It reveals the protocol sequence underneath: transport, ClientSession, initialize, list_tools, call_tool. Real hosts add model orchestration and user consent on top.",
     "diagram": "sequenceDiagram\nparticipant Script as client py\nparticipant Server as server py\nScript->>Server: launch via stdio\nScript->>Server: initialize\nServer-->>Script: capabilities\nScript->>Server: tools list\nServer-->>Script: add tool\nScript->>Server: tools call add\nServer-->>Script: result five",
     "code": {
      "language": "python",
      "caption": "Runnable minimal client for the server example",
      "content": "# client.py\n# Install in a project environment: python -m pip install mcp\n# Place next to server.py, then run: python client.py\n\nimport asyncio\nfrom mcp import ClientSession, StdioServerParameters\nfrom mcp.client.stdio import stdio_client\n\nasync def main() -> None:\n    server = StdioServerParameters(command=\"python\", args=[\"server.py\"])\n\n    async with stdio_client(server) as (read, write):\n        async with ClientSession(read, write) as session:\n            await session.initialize()\n\n            tools = await session.list_tools()\n            print(\"tools:\", [tool.name for tool in tools.tools])\n\n            result = await session.call_tool(\"add\", {\"a\": 2, \"b\": 3})\n            print(\"result:\", result)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    asyncio.run(main())\n"
     },
