     "firstPrinciples": "First principles: an incident is not a single event; it is a state machine. The system must move from uncertainty to ownership, from ownership to impact reduction, from impact reduction to closure, and from closure to learning.",
     "definition": "A practical lifecycle is new to acknowledged to mitigated to resolved to postmortem. Some organizations add detected, triaged, contained, recovered, or closed, but the core shape remains ownership, action, stabilization, closure, and learning.",
     "analogy": "Picture a hospital emergency room: patient arrives, triage accepts the case, doctors stabilize the patient, discharge happens when safe, and a review improves future care.",
     "mentalModel": "Every MCP write tool should respect the lifecycle. Acknowledge moves ownership, update adds evidence, mitigate records impact reduction, resolve closes active response, and postmortem records preventive work. Do not let an agent skip states without policy.",
     "diagram": "stateDiagram-v2\nNew --> Acknowledged\nAcknowledged --> Mitigated\nMitigated --> Resolved\nResolved --> Postmortem\nAcknowledged --> Escalated\nEscalated --> Mitigated",
     "code": {
      "language": "python",
      "caption": "Representative incident state machine",
      "content": "# Representative lifecycle guardrail for an incident MCP connector.\nALLOWED_TRANSITIONS = {\n    \"new\": {\"acknowledged\"},\n    \"acknowledged\": {\"mitigated\", \"escalated\"},\n    \"escalated\": {\"mitigated\"},\n    \"mitigated\": {\"resolved\"},\n    \"resolved\": {\"postmortem\"},\n}\n\ndef can_transition(current: str, desired: str) -> bool:\n    return desired in ALLOWED_TRANSITIONS.get(current, set())\n\nprint(can_transition(\"new\", \"resolved\"))       # False: too much authority for one jump.\nprint(can_transition(\"new\", \"acknowledged\"))  # True: normal first response.\n"
     },
