     "firstPrinciples": "First principles: automation that can change planning, code review, or deployment state can create real operational damage. Approval is not ceremony; it is the control surface where humans verify intent before side effects.",
     "definition": "Write actions include creating or updating work items, adding comments, linking artifacts, creating branches, opening or updating pull requests, creating wiki pages, creating test plans, and queueing or modifying pipeline runs. Foundry MCP guidance recommends requiring approval for high risk operations and reviewing tool names and arguments before approval.",
     "analogy": "Read tools are reconnaissance. Write tools are live fire. A live fire command needs a range officer.",
     "mentalModel": "The policy is simple: read only by default, allow list tools, require approval always for writes, log arguments and outcomes, and separate permissions so a read only agent cannot queue a deployment even if it tries.",
     "diagram": "graph TD\nToolRequest[Tool request] --> IsWrite[Is write]\nIsWrite -->|No| Execute[Execute and log]\nIsWrite -->|Yes| Review[Show arguments]\nReview --> Approve[Human approves]\nApprove --> Execute\nApprove --> Deny[Deny and explain]",
     "code": {
      "language": "python",
      "caption": "Approval policy evaluator",
      "content": "write_tools = {'wit_work_item_write', 'repo_pull_request_write', 'pipelines_write', 'wiki_upsert_page'}\n\ndef approval_required(tool_name: str) -> bool:\n    return tool_name in write_tools or tool_name.endswith('_write')\n\nfor name in ['wit_work_item', 'wit_work_item_write', 'pipelines_run', 'pipelines_write']:\n    print(name, 'approval required:', approval_required(name))\n"
     },
